1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 { The move order with 2.Nf3 has fallen somewhat out of favor in lieu of 2.Bf4, but both have their merits. } (2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 { [%cal Gg8f6] } 3... Nc6 4. c3 Qb6! { In accordance with White delaying Nf3, we delay ...Nf6 to make sure White has less time to prepare for ...Qb6. } (4... Nf6 5. Nd2! { shows one main point of this move order relative to the others, as now } 5... Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qc2 Bf5? { just hangs a piece. }) 5. Qb3 c4 6. Qc2 e5! { is an exciting line and my main recommendation here - see Chapter 5 for all of the details. } (6... Bf5 7. Qxf5 Qxb2 8. Qxd5 { [%cal Gg8f6,Gg1f3] } 8... Qxa1 9. Qb5! { [%cal Gb5b2,Ga1b1,Gb2b1] }) 7. dxe5 Bf5 8. Qc1) 2... Nf6 { For most double-queen pawn players, this move will be the easiest, since White still has the option of going 3.c4, transposing back to the Queen's Gambit. This preserves most of the important options in that case. Moves like 2...e6 or 2...c6 are possible but will exclude certain players from being able to use this repertoire. } 3. Bf4 { This is the move that defines the London System. White develops the bishop to f4, outside of the pawn chain, with the intent to bolster the central dark squares via e3 and c3 instead of building the tension in the center with c4 a la the Queen's Gambit. White is essentially inviting a Slav Reversed should black play most principally with ...c5. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Ge2e3,Gc2c3,Gb1d2] } (3. c3!? { was the choice of Le Quang Liem in his Chessable Lifetime Repertoire on the London System. White literally plays a reversed Slav Defense, trying to discourage ...c5 by making a more that is more useful should he try to capture and hold the c5-pawn. We play it anyway, and see Chapter 4 for a detailed breakdown of the position resulting after } 3... c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. b4 a5 6. e3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4 bxc5 11. b5 $13) 3... c5 { Black takes the opportunity to introduce tension in the center, initiating a reversed Queen's Gambit Declined or Slav. } 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 { This has historically been the main move and one that is most consistent with White's overall strategy, but has fallen on hard times because of the continuation below. Because of that, White has moved towards 5.Nbd2! first, ensuring that the threat to the b2-pawn is less severe should black venture ...Qb6. } (5. Nbd2! { was developed as a response to 5.c3 Qb6! - White develops the queenside a bit first, making sure that the threat to the b2-pawn is less severe. } 5... Nh5!? { is a nice, combative option and my recommendation - see Chapter 3 for the analysis of this line. } (5... Qb6 6. dxc5! { As a consequence of White's move order choice, this is now an option since the threat to b2 is less severe. } 6... Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8. Bb5 $36)) 5... Qb6! { This is a key move, exploiting one of the main downsides to Bf4 - the weak b2-pawn (White does similar with Qb3 in the normal Slav). } 6. Qb3 c4! 7. Qc2 (7. Qxb6?! axb6 { is positionally generous for Black - White can't stop ...b5-b4 and Black is more than happy to open the a-file and convert the a-pawn to a more central b-pawn. } { [%cal Ga8a2,Bb6b5,Bb5b4] }) 7... Bf5! { A key position that's discussed in Chapter 2. } 8. Qc1 *


[Event "An Attacking Repertoire AGAINST the London: 2.Nf3 and the Old Move - 5.c3"]
[Date "2022.01.07"]
[White "London"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "TonyRo"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D02"]
[Opening "Queen's Pawn Game: London System"]
[StudyName "An Attacking Repertoire AGAINST the London"]
[ChapterName "2.Nf3 and the Old Move - 5.c3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kKcyAydw/c200XRSt"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 { This is perhaps the "classic" or slightly less modern version
of the London, as people have since discovered that there are at least some
nuances and small benefits to delaying Nf3 if you're strictly set on the
London. But really it comes down to taste and which main positions you're
interested in reaching. Le Quang Liem prefers this move, and other authors
like Sedlak and Romero Holmes prefer 2.Bf4 instead. } 2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6! { and now White has two ways to protect the b-pawn, with b3 being the main
choice for her majesty: } { [%cal Gb6b2] } 6. Qb3 (6. Qc2 g6! (6... Nh5!? { is playable as
well, but if White plays principally and enters the complications after } 7. Be5 { then Black has little opportunity to really play for a win, e.g. } 7... f6 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9. Bd4 Qa5 10. b4 Qc7 11. c4 e5 12. cxd5 exd4 13. dxc6 Bxb4+ 14. Nbd2 dxe3 15. fxe3 Qxc6 16. Qb3 Qc3 17. Qxc3 Bxc3 18. Rc1 Bxd2+ 19. Kxd2 O-O { A.Nickel - M.Semrl, Correspondence 2017 }) 7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. h3 O-O 9. Be2 Nd7 10. O-O e5 { V.Laznicka - D.Nisipeanu, Bundesliga 2018 }) 6... c4! { A
strategically risky move in a way - Black removes the central tension, and if
White is allowed b3 and we have to exchange, we'd be very unhappy to trade
c-pawn for a-pawn. Here we're happy to do it, as White has to lose further
time after Qc2 and generally won't find time for the b3-break until it's not
much of a worry anymore. } { [%cal Gb3b6,Ga7b6] } 7. Qc2 { [%cal Gb2b3] } 7... Bf5! 8. Qc1 Nh5!? (8... e6 9. Nbd2 { and now 9...Be7 or 9...h6 has been played the most - also good and worth
looking into if 8...Nh5 isn't your thing or runs into problems. }) 9. Bg3 (9. Bg5 f6! 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 e5 12. dxe5 (12. Be2 O-O-O 13. b3 cxb3 14. axb3 Nxg3 { of F.Hellers - J.Pechac, correspondence 2021 is also quite bad for White.
Black can go ...Kb8 and look to play on either the e-file or the c-file after
a quick ...exd4. }) 12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nxe5 (13... fxe5!? { is also possible
since } 14. Nxg5 Rg8 15. Nf3 O-O-O 16. Nbd2 { allows the smashing blow } 16... Rxg3!! 17. fxg3 Qxe3+ 18. Be2 Bd3 19. Qd1 Bc5 20. Rf1 e4 $19 { with a completely
winning attack }) 14. Nxe5 fxe5 15. Nd2 O-O-O $19 { D.Paravyan - A.Kukhmazov,
internet blitz 2020. Black has played this variation a few times in the last
two years and has scored well. }) (9. Be5 f6! 10. Bg3 e5 11. Be2 Nxg3 12. hxg3 O-O-O $17 { The two bishops and stronger central presence make it clear that
Black is better. } { [%csl Gf5,Gf8,Ye5,Yd5,Yc4] }) 9... Nxg3 10. hxg3 g6 11. Nbd2 Bg7 $15 { E.Ermakov - A.
Kosteniuk, internet blitz 2020. This position has been reached in 14 games in
my database - Black has scored +5 -2 =7, and Stockfish prefers the second
player as well by a smidge. The two bishops, more active development, and
extra central space must count for something. } *


[Event "An Attacking Repertoire AGAINST the London: 2.Nf3 and the New Move - 5.Nbd2!"]
