1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 a6!? { Already quite a rare idea, something like an accelerated Chebanenko Slav. Black's idea is really three-fold: the main point is that now Black may really be threatening to grab on c4 and keep it with ...b5, but also remains flexible with regards to the development of their other pieces until White discloses extra information, and may challenge White's c4-pawn directly with ...b5 in the future as well. } { [%cal Rd5c4,Yb7b5] } (3... Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 { would be a more normal Chebanenko, but as we'll see in the game, Black does indeed make good use of delaying ...Nf6, for better or worse! }) 4. e3 { This is certainly the most sensible option given Black's possible threat of ...dxc4, though other moves like 4.Nc3, 4.g3, or even 4.c5, are also good. } 4... e6 5. Bd3 f5?! { These are the spots where being an annotator is difficult - objectively I can't help but feel that this is just an inaccuracy (it's very fun to try these types of things out in blitz...for science), but I also love that Black has been consistent with the idea and is attempting to justify 3...a6. The problem is that ...a6 is just not at all useful in Stonewall Dutch structures, which already can feel a smidge dodgy unless you're ultra-precise. } { [%csl Ra6] } (5... Nf6 { would be more normal here, but then we wouldn't have this fine game to look at! } 6. b3 c5!? (6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Be7 8. O-O b6 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Qc2 O-O 11. e4 $14 { Fuller, William E. - Zajsek, Franc, 1/2-1/2, GER/M/08-E (GER), 2019, https://lichess.org/AhU91awf }) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. O-O Nc6 9. Bb2 Bg4 10. Be2 Bd6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Rc1 $14 { Gurevich, Mikhail - Lautier, Joel, 1-0, Reykjavik Edda rapid, 2003, https://lichess.org/feeflFNM }) (5... dxc4! { is probably Black's best bet for equality at this point, humorously transposing back to a Queen's Gambit Accepted with one extra move (Black has lost a tempo with ...c6-c5 and White with Bd3xc4) after } 6. Bxc4 c5 7. O-O Nf6 $10 { etc. }) 6. O-O Nd7?! { Black is going a bit too far with the non-standard development at this point - I don't totally see the benefit of starting this way, but there is one very noticeable downside. } (6... Nf6 { is, again, also reasonable. }) (6... Bd6!? 7. b3 Qe7 { would be a more standard Stonewall approach, stopping White from trading the dark-squared bishops without making any concessions. } { [%cal Rc1a3,Gg8f6,Ge8g8] }) 7. b3 { A standard and good move, but White misses a nice little nuance. } (7. cxd5! { was probably better - in Stonewall structures Black always wants to be able to respond to this move with ...exd5 but can't here because the knight on d7 interferes with the defense of the f-pawn. Engines point out a very nice way to trade off the dark-squares as well here, e.g. } 7... cxd5 8. Bd2! Ngf6 9. Qa4 Bd6 10. Bb4! $16) 7... Ngf6 8. Ba3! { In these Dutch Stonewall structures, the bad and good bishops are fairly well defined. White usually does well to exchange dark-squared bishops for obvious reasons - Black's remaining prelate on c8 is going to require some care to find a reasonable and active home. } { [%csl Ya3,Rc8,Gf8,Rb7,Rc6,Rd5,Re6,Rf5] } 8... Bxa3 9. Nxa3 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ga3c2,Gc2e1,Ge1d3,Gd3e5] } 9... O-O 10. Nc2 { One thing Black does have going for them is that generally White would like to focus on the e5-square with Nce1-d3 but it's a bit tougher here with the light-squared bishop on that square. } 10... Ne4 11. Nce1 Rf6?! { Again, since this is a blitz game (and both of these players are actually stronger blitz players than me!) it's tough to criticize any move too much. With that said, I have a hard time believing in this kind of strategy - the physics of chess just simply don't allow you to move second, waste a move on the ...a6 pawn push, trade off your best minor piece, and then carry out a successful mating attack anyway. } { [%cal Rf6h6,Rg7g5,Rg5g4,Yd8h4] } 12. Ne5!? { This is fine, but it does seem a bit counterintuitive to me to plug up that weak square on e5. } (12. Be2 $16 { would have probably been my choice, continuing with the usual plan of stuffing a knight into e5 uncontested. }) 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Rh6 14. f4 { This is a strong defensive move. White needs the e1-knight back on f3 to cover f2 and keep the Black queen out of h4, but chucks the pawn out in front first. This dissuades a future ...g5-g4, stops ...Ng5 (which would remove the defender of f2), defends the e5-pawn, gives White the option of Ng5 down the road, and clears out the second rank should White need extra defenders that way. } { [%cal Ge1f3] } (14. f3? Qh4! 15. h3 Ng5 $40 { [%cal Rg5h3] }) 14... Qh4 { Again, I think this is a little too on the nose, but in a blitz game you've really gone too far to come back now. } (14... Bd7 $16) 15. Nf3 (15. h3? { inverting the move order is a mistake here, as White would cede the g3-square, e.g. } 15... Bd7 16. Nf3 Qg3 $40 { [%cal Rh6h3] }) 15... Qh5 16. h3! { With the h-pawn defended, White is ready to make a second positive trade of minor pieces with Bxe4, leaving Black with that sad guy on c8 versus a wonderful knight on d4, for instance. } { [%csl Gf3,Rc8,Ra8][%cal Gd3e4] } 16... Rg6 17. Bxe4? { The only blemish on this game, though it's not obvious why! } (17. Kh2! { stops the slimy 17...Qxh3 idea, after which White still has the same positional threat of taking on e4. }) 17... fxe4? { In a blitz game 99.9% of the playing population would premove this, but Black missed a wonderful shot: } (17... Qxh3! 18. Ng5 Qxe3+ 19. Rf2 (19. Kh2?? fxe4 { is winning for Black since the Qh5 resource no longer works on account of } 20. Qh5 Rh6 $19) 19... Rxg5! (19... fxe4? 20. Qh5 $18) 20. fxg5 Qxe4 $13 { with an absolute mess, but one in which I don't think Black is much worse, if at all. }) 18. Ng5! { Here this is the only square that stops ...Qxh3, but also comes with a very nasty idea. } 18... Qxd1 19. Raxd1 h6 20. Nxe4! { An excellent shot played very quickly - White is a strong player and understands immediately that Black won't find a way to unravel their clogged development. } (20. h4!? { It's hilarious to me that this also wins - Black's position is so fundamentally broken that simply accepting the loss of the piece is good enough on account of the stuck Rg6. } 20... hxg5 21. fxg5 Bd7 (21... b5! 22. c5 b4 $16) 22. Kh2! $18 { and Black can't easily stop the king walk to g4 and the pawn push to h5, trapping the rook. }) 20... dxe4 21. Rd8+ Kh7 22. Rfd1 { Quite a lovely position really. Not only is Black's queenside paralyzed, as a result of the over-optimistic rook lift Black's rook is basically also completely stuck. Despite being down a piece, White is winning easily - there's no defense to Rf8, Rdd8, followed by taking the bishop on c8. After that, Black's pieces are still quarantined on the kingside whilst the White rook mops up on the other side of the board. } { [%csl Rc8,Ra8,Yg6,Yh7][%cal Gd8e8,Ge8f8,Gd1d8] } 22... b5 23. c5 { There's no way for Black to get active or open lines. } 23... a5 24. Re8 a4 25. b4 a3 (25... Bb7 { was pointed out by many as a better defense, though } 26. Rxa8 Bxa8 27. Rd7 $18 { is simple enough, trapping the bishop after Ra7. Black has the same problem mentioned previously - Black's rook and king are simply too far away from the queenside to defend. } { [%csl Ra8,Yg6,Yh7][%cal Gd7a7] }) 26. Rdd8 { Brutal - it would be enough to win the piece back, but the only way to stop the mate on h8 is to give up the rook on g6 as well. A really nice positional game from White, with accurate play out of the opening followed by a very beautiful exploitation of Black's over-ambitious attempt at kingside play. } 1-0


