1. c4 { An aside: my first chess coach has wonderfully silly phrases for nearly every scenario that occurs on a chess board, and would always call the English Opening (which I have played for most of my chess career) the "Paul Revere". Do with that what you will. } 1... e6 2. a3?! { My database has 82923 games that start 1.c4 e6, and only 67 (that's less than one tenth of one percent!) of them continue with 2.a3, and probably for good reason. White wants to avoid a future ...Bb4, expand on the queenside with b4, or just enter standard opening positions reversed with a3 as an extra move (see Awonder Liang's recent attempt at this strategy versus Lenier Dominguez in the recent US Championship). In any case, this is too far out there and too much of a violation of normal opening principles (neglects development, lack of central influence) to really worry black. } (2. d4 d5 3. Nc3! (3. cxd5?! { would also be too early, since Black can develop the bishop more actively on f5 before White gets to that diagonal with Bd3, for example } 3... exd5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Nf3 Bf5 { [%csl Gf5] }) 3... Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 { reaches one of the most iconic opening positions of all time, the Queen's Gambit Exchange variation. Note that relative to the game, Bg5 is infinitely more useful than a3. } 5... c6 6. e3 (6. Qc2 { is also a good try, e.g., } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Gc2f5,Rc8f5] }) 6... Bf5!? { This is not the best move, but I show it here to illustrate how White's opening choices make it a bit more difficult to get the ideal ...c6 + ...Bf5 set-up without get scratched. } 7. Qf3! Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 { =/ and White is probably a smidge better based on Black's wrecked pawn structure. Even still, this position is playable for Black, who has the two bishops as compensation. } { Carlsen, M. - Kramnik, Vladimir, 1-0, 4th Norway Chess 2016, https://lichess.org/b6Ltr4hi } { [%csl Yf6,Yf7,Yh7] }) 2... d5 3. cxd5?! { I'm not a huge fan of releasing the tension like this so early. Generally, White building up the pressure on d5 and forcing Black to release it with ...dxc4 yields a central majority and more space for White, whereas here White cedes a totally symmetrical structure and opens up Black's light-squared bishop for easy development. } 3... exd5 4. d4 $10 { Depending on how you'd like to look at it, we've reached either a decidely sub-optimal Queen's Gambit Exchange for White (see my comments on move 2), or a reversed Caro-Kann Exchange with a3 tossed in for free. The first player has scored around 25% from here in my database, which seems more gloomy than it really should be for a roughly equal position. } { [%csl Ra3] } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 c5!? { This is a logical decision given White's insertion of a3 instead of any reasonable developing move - Black opens up the game to exploit the lack of development. } (5... c6 6. Nf3 Bf5 { is a more banal choice in line with my notes on move 2, but is obviously good as well. }) 6. e3 (6. dxc5? { would already be problematic for White after } 6... d4! $17 { , and get even worse should they fall for the thematic } 7. Nb5? Qa5+! $19 { dropping the steed. }) (6. Nf3! { would be my choice and is more in line with standard principles. Here, White can still entertain the idea of developing the dark-squared bishop more actively. }) 6... Nc6 7. dxc5 (7. Nf3 { I think stronger players would prefer to stick the knight here immediately. It's reasonable to argue that you know it's going there anyway, which allows White to stay flexible elsewhere. Additionally, in these types of positions it's usually worth waiting on dxc5 for a few moves to see if Black will be forced to play something like ...Be7, after which dxc5 would gain a tempo. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd6 { transposes back to a position reached via a more common Symmetrical English move order. Play might continue } 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. Nf3 a6 12. b4 Bb8 13. Bb2 Qd6 { [%cal Rd5d4] } 14. g3 Bh3 15. Re1 Ba7 16. Bf1 Bxf1 17. Rxf1 Rad8 18. Ne2 Ne4 $10 { Goldenberg, Igor - Neubauer, Martin, 1/2-1/2, WMSG Rapid Team 1st, 2008, https://lichess.org/XfI9W0p8 }) 7... Bxc5 8. b4?! { Another pawn move on the queenside, another missed opportunity for standard development... } (8. Nf3 { Again, just play the obvious developing move, geez! }) 8... d4! { A very classy exploitation of White's lackadaisical play thus far - Black further opens the center with White's king many moves away from safety. } (8... Bb6?! 9. Na4! Bc7 (9... d4 { would be too late now after } 10. Nxb6 Qxb6 11. Nf3 { and White is comfortable }) 10. Nf3 { would let White off the hook. }) 9. Nb5 (9. exd4?? { gets absolutely roasted by standard coffeehouse attacks on f2/h2, e.g., } 9... Bxd4 10. Bb2 Ng4! 11. Nh3 O-O 12. Be2 Qh4 13. O-O Be5 $19) 9... Bb6 10. Bb2? { This is the straw that breaks the camel's back - again, White just refuses to develop their kingside, perhaps banking on this Nd6+ idea after Black's next. The opening has been a failure for the first player, who needs roughly 3 more tempi to slide over to g1! } 10... dxe3 11. Nd6+? { I am so thankful White went for this, because if they didn't the lichess audience wouldn't have such a wonderful game! Now Black wins spectacularly, with a cascade of sacrifices that I suspect would have made even Tal jealous! } (11. Qxd8+ Bxd8 12. fxe3 O-O $17 { might have been palatable - the trade of queens eases White's defensive task some. }) 11... Qxd6!! $19 { Winning on the spot and totally spectacular, guaranteeing the time Black needs to munch all the way down to g1! These are the kinds of moves you love to play over the board! You get to confidently smash that queen down on d6 whilst taking in your opponent's facial expressions... } (11... Ke7 12. Nxc8+ Qxc8 $19 { is also winning on account of White not being able to get their king to safety before their kingside vaporizes, but is substantially less flashy and fun. }) 12. Qxd6 exf2+ 13. Ke2 fxg1=Q 14. Rxg1 Bg4+ { Again Black disregards material in favor of time, eschewing the Rg1 for speedier development and a brutal attack. } 15. Ke1 Rd8 (15... Bf2+! 16. Kxf2 Ne4+ $19 { would have been the final, flashy nail in the coffin! I'd like to believe Black saw this but was insistent on winning this game sans queen. }) 16. Qf4 O-O 17. Bxf6 Rfe8+! { The only move, but a great one! Again, Black trades more material for time, achieving perfectly centralized and harmonious development. Just look at those pieces! Really beautiful play from Black! } { [%csl Re1][%cal Bg4d1,Bb6g1,Ge8e1,Gd8d1] } 18. Be5 Rxe5+ (18... Nxe5! { (apparently) mates by force after } 19. Bb5 Nd3+ 20. Kd2 Nxf4+ 21. Kc2 Rc8+ 22. Kb2 Bd4+ 23. Ka2 Be6+ 24. Kb1 Bf5+ 25. Ka2 Rc2+ 26. Kb3 Rc3+ 27. Ka2 Ree3 28. Bd3 Rcxd3 29. Kb1 Rc3+ 30. Kb2 Re2# { , but this is quite a bit less aesthetically pleasing than the game continuation. }) 19. Qxe5 { This is a tough pill to swallow, but what else? } (19. Be2 Rxe2+ 20. Kf1 Ra2! { is a beautiful variation that illustrates White's problems. White cannot stop mate, and so should perhaps just allow } 21. Rxa2 Rd1# { for the crowd. }) 19... Nxe5 20. Rh1 Be3 (20... Nf3+!? 21. gxf3 Bxf3 $19 { trapping the rook, was also cute. }) 21. Be2 Rd2! { Black finds the cleanest kill, and White obliges by allowing very pretty mate in 5. } 22. Bxg4 { Black's skeleton crew gets the job done, picturesquely mating in a line along the 3rd rank. } 22... Nd3+ 23. Kf1 Rf2+ 24. Kg1 Rf3# { Quite a symbolic finish - White's king perishes on the g1-square, a square that would have guaranteed an easier game had his majesty arrived there roughly 15 moves ago via standard development schemes and castling. Both rooks didn't move once. A breathtaking game and a wonderful example of energetic play exploiting slow development and a king in the center. Morphy couldn't have played it better himself, and in a 10-minute blitz game at that. Bravo! } { [%csl Gf3,Ge3,Gd3,Rh1,Rg1,Ra1] } 0-1


