{ As is common in endings, the rook pawn is an annoying exception. We've already seen that this is an easy win with a b,d,e, or g-pawn, but here (along with bishop pawns) is a draw due to a cute stalemate motif, for instance: }
1. Qb5+ (1. Qd4+ Kb1 2. Qb4+ Ka1! { illustrates the same idea. }) 1... Ka1! $10 { Already we see the issue - when Black's king blocks the a-pawn, White can't move advance his king, as it would immediately result in a stalemate. } { [%cal Gb5b4] } 2. Qa4 Kb1 3. Qb3+ Ka1! { and so on - White can't make progress. } 4. Qa3 *


