[Event "Alekhine's Defense Overview: Introduction"]
[Date "2021.12.23"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B04"]
[Opening "Alekhine Defense: Modern Variation"]
[StudyName "Alekhine's Defense Overview"]
[ChapterName "Introduction"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/yIC5Aghz/TmYhFsoA"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/TonyRo"]
[UTCDate "2021.12.23"]
[UTCTime "02:52:47"]

{ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ImC6zs9I2dE }
1. e4 Nf6 { The characteristic move of Alekhine's Defense - Black attacks the e4-pawn immediately, tempting White to push it further forward. Black hopes that White will overextend, allow a weakness on c5, or (after ...d6), exchange off his e-pawn for Black's c-pawn. } 2. e5 Nd5 { Perhaps first played in a correspondence game in 1890 (there is a game feature Napoleon Bonaparte that's earlier but generally considered fake), the Alekhine didn't become popular until it's namesake played it in the early 1920's. See the next chapter. After that, the most notable outing was games 13 and 19 in the 1972 Fischer-Spassky match, including a win for Fischer. Nowadays many GMs including Nakamura, Kamsky, Ivanchuk, and Carlsen play the Alekhine on occasion. } 3. d4 d6 { Black starts to chip away. } 4. Nf3 { This is the Classical variation - White is content with a small, nagging edge, and will usually follow up with straightforward development, for instance Be2, O-O, c4 then Nc3, etc. } (4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 { The Four Pawns Attack - White spends the maximum amount of time grabbing the maximum amount of space. This is the most critical variation and White's main attempt at all-out refutation. }) (4. exd6 cxd6 5. c4 Nb6 { is the Exchange Variation. White is content with the d4/c4 group of pawns in the center and hopes to restrict Black's pieces development on the queenside by bolstering the long diagonal and the c4-square. Black, on the other hand, will try to equalize the space in the center with ...d5 or ...e5, putting his extra e-pawn to good work. Again, see the chapters on the "Power of the e-pawn" for more on this structure. }) *


