[SetUp "1"]

{ Behind the e-pawn black centralized his pieces.Once the e- and f-pawns move
forward whites king will be in danger of suffocation.The white queenside
majority doesnt represent any danger as whites pieces are too passive to turn
it into an asset. }
23... Qc3! { The penetration of the queen forces a
concession. } 24. Qc1 (24. Re3 Qf6 25. c5 Rd8 $15 { and black takes over the
d-file }) 24... Qxc1 25. Rxc1 Rd8 $15 { [%cal Gg8e5] } 26. g3 (26. f3!) 26... Kf7 27. c5 Kf6 { Behind his advanced
pawns blacks king immediately took up an influential position.Hes ready to
support the advance of the kingside pawns and can keep an eye on the white
c-pawn at the same time. Meanwhile whites king is far from the center of
attention,as he lacks space to creep out of his box. } 28. Bc4 { Understandably,
suffering from lack of space white wants to ease his task by exchanges. } (28. c6) 28... Bc8! { Keeping
bishops on the board will allow black to develop an attack on whites king
after g5,f4 and the opening of the kingside.And the white Bishop actually
obstructs the support of whites c-pawn. } (28... Bxc4 29. Rxc4 Ke5 30. c6) 29. a4 g5 30. b5 f4 31. Kf1 Rd2 32. Ke1 Rb2 33. gxf4 gxf4 34. Be2 (34. c6 f3 35. Bd5 b6) 34... Ke5 { Thanks to the central majority we see a huge difference
between the 2 kings.While black has one more piece in play,whites king is
mainly a source of concern,being restricted to the first rank and facing a
slow but dangerous attack. } 35. c6 bxc6 36. Rxc6? (36. bxc6 { Had to be tried.
It leaves the c-pawn very vulnerable but glues the black Bishop to c8. }) 36... Be6 $19 { The black bishop comes back into play and blacks positional
domination already leaves white defenceless against a coming breakthrough with
f3 and e3. } 37. Bd1 (37. Rc1 f3 38. Bd1 e3 39. Bxf3 Rxf2) 37... Rb1 38. Rc5+ Kd4 39. Rc2 e3 40. fxe3+ fxe3 41. Rc6 Bg4 42. Rd6+ Ke5 43. h3 Bh5 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


