1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 (2. Nc3 d5 (2... e5! { transposes directly to a Vienna. }) 3. e5 { [%cal Gf6e4] } (3. exd5 Nxd5 4. Bc4 Nb6 5. Bb3 Nc6 (5... c5!? { is more enterprising }) 6. Nf3 Bf5 (6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 { seems solid enough for Black as well. })) 3... Nfd7 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gd7e5] } (3... Ne4 4. Nce2!) 4. f4 { [%cal Gc3d5] } 4... e6 5. d4 c5 6. Nf3 { transposes to a Classical French. }) (2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 { [%csl Gf6] } 3... c5 (3... e5!?) 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 e5! 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 (8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Re1 f6 10. c3 Kh8!) 8... d4! $15) (2. Bc4? Nxe4 3. Bxf7+ Kxf7 4. Qh5+ Kg8 5. Qd5+ e6 6. Qxe4 d5 7. Qe2 Nc6 $17 { Hering, Hartmut - Bonfissuto, Giulio, 0-1, DJ-CT18/sf02, 2013, https://lichess.org/Vyi0TkoJ } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ge6e5] }) 2... Nd5 (2... Ng8 { is kind of a silly move that has been tried a bit in quick time controls here and there. As far as I can tell the main idea is to try and procure a French Advance where the light-squared bishop is not trapped behind the pawn chain (even at the expense of a few moves) e.g. } 3. d4 d5 4. Bd3!? { White makes every effort to freeze out the light-squared bishop that Black is trying so hard to activate. } (4. c4! { also seems quite strong - it seems logical to open up the game as much as possible to exploit Black's loss of time. }) 4... c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. f3 Bh5 8. Nf4 Bg6 { O'Donnell, Tom - Fuster, Geza, 1-0, Oakham House, 1988, https://lichess.org/D0wt8Zar } 9. e6! $16 $146) 3. c4 (3. Nc3 Nxc3 { [%cal Gd2c3] } 4. dxc3 (4. bxc3 { allows Black to consider entering a position that looks like the French Winawer. Black has lost some time but has not been forced to block his light-squared bishop in or trade off his dark-squared bishop, e.g. } 4... d5 5. d4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be2 Bg4 $13 { Heidenfeld, Mark - Baburin, Alexander, 1/2-1/2, BCF-ch 86th, 1999, https://lichess.org/td2FA8ME }) 4... d6 5. Nf3 Nc6 (5... dxe5!? { has been played by some strong players and actually seems logical in a way. For the price of their castling rights, Black heads to an ending where he has an active majority on the kingside, while the same cannot be said about White on the other flank. } 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nxe5 Ke8 { Sedlak, Nikola - Spraggett, Kevin, 1/2-1/2, Kostic Memorial 15th, 2008, https://lichess.org/jjqYhAfs }) 6. Bb5 Bd7 (6... g6!? { also seems good }) 7. Qe2 e6 8. Bf4 a6 9. Bd3 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Bd6 11. Bg3 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bc6 13. O-O-O Qe7 $10 { Mrdja, Milan - Laketic, Gojko, 1/2-1/2, Codogno op 3rd, 2011, https://lichess.org/ONOJ9b1r }) (3. d4 d6 4. Bc4 { uses a cute Qh5 double-attack idea to keep the balance, though I don't think Black should be at all worried however. They can use White's bishop as a target on the queenside, for instance } 4... Nb6 5. Bb3 dxe5 6. Qh5 { [%cal Gh5f7,Gh5e5] } 6... e6 7. dxe5 a5 8. a4 Na6 9. Nf3 Nc5 $10 { Milosevic, Goran - Baburin, Alexander, 0-1, SUI-chI op, 1992, https://lichess.org/lwRYLkQE }) 3... Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 { is the Chase variation, named so for obvious reasons. } { [%cal Gb1c3,Gd2d4,Gf1c4] } 5. Nc3 e6 *


