1. g4 d5 2. h3 h5! 3. g5 (3. Bg2 hxg4 4. hxg4 Rxh1 5. Bxh1 { A.
Benend-T.Link, German League 2001 } 5... e5! $146 { White already finds the threat
of ...Qh4, harrassing White's kingside pieces (perhaps on h2), and the
tenderness of f2 already tricky to deal with, for example: } { [%cal Gd8h4,Yf8c5,Yg8f6,Yf6g4] } 6. d4 (6. c4 Qh4! 7. Bxd5 (7. Bg2 Nf6! 8. cxd5? Nxg4 9. Nh3 Bc5 10. e3 Nh2! $19) 7... Nf6 { [%csl Gg4] } 8. Qb3!? { [%cal Yb3b7,Yb3g3] } 8... c6 (8... Nxg4 { allows } 9. Qg3 { and is therefore probably a little less of a clean
kill. }) 9. Bf3 (9. Bg2 Bc5 10. e3 Nxg4 11. Nh3 Nh2 $19) 9... Bc5 10. e3 (10. d4 Nxg4 11. Bxg4 Qxg4 12. dxc5 Qxg1+ 13. Kd2 Qxf2 $19) 10... e4 11. Bg2 Nxg4 12. Nh3 Ne5 $19 { and White collapses. } { [%cal Ge5d3,Gc8h3] }) 6... Nc6! 7. dxe5 (7. g5 exd4 $19) 7... Qh4! 8. Bxd5 Bc5! 9. e3 (9. Bxf7+ Kf8! 10. e3 Kxf7 11. Qd5+ Be6 12. Qxc5 Qh1 $19) 9... Bxg4 $19) (3. gxh5!? { Ugly, leaving Black at
structural disadvantage, but probably no worse than the other moves. } 3... e5 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 (5. c4 dxc4 6. Qa4+ c6 7. Qxc4 { and almost anything is great for
Black here, e.g. } 7... Be6 8. Qa4 Nbd7 $17 { [%cal Gd7c5] }) 5... Nc6 6. c3 Rxh5 7. Nf3 { U.Wiese-R.
Sand, Correspondence 2012 } 7... Bc5 $146 { -/+/+- }) 3... e5 { [%cal Gd8g5] } 4. d3 (4. h4 Nc6 5. Bg2 Bg4 6. Nf3 Qd7) (4. d4 exd4 5. Nf3 (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qa4 { B.Blankeburg-H.Kleinsorgen, Correspondence 2003 } 6... Bc5 $19 { is a reversed Scandinavian (!?) where Black has Bc5 and h5 for free
in exchange for h3 and g4-g5. No surprise that this is horrible for White. }) 5... c5 $17 { and I very much doubt White has any compensation for the pawn
whatsoever. }) 4... Ne7 { [%csl Gg6][%cal Ge7g6] } 5. Bg2 Be6 (5... Nbc6 6. Nf3 Ng6 7. a3 Be6 $19) 6. Nc3 Nbc6 7. Nf3 Ng6 { Black's knight is excellently placed on
this square. } 8. e4 { White logically grasps at a small share in the center. } 8... d4 9. Ne2 { T.Heedt-H.Kleinsorgen, Correspondence 2004 } 9... Qd7 $146 { Fundamentally
White's problem is that his kingside is wrecked and Black has more space.Under
these constraints it's simply too hard for him to organize his pieces
harmoniously or generate counterplay. Black just castling long and seeks play
in the center or kingside with the f-pawn jumping to f6 or f5. } { [%cal Ge6h3,Ge8c8,Yf8e7,Yf7f6,Yf6f5] } (9... Qd6 10. h4 O-O-O 11. a3 Qd7 12. Ng3 Bg4 13. Bd2 f6 14. Qc1 Kb8 15. b4 a6 16. Qb2 Nf4 $19 { K.Hursky-I.Siger, Correspondence 2009 }) 10. c3 (10. Bd2 O-O-O 11. a3 f6 $19) (10. h4 O-O-O 11. a3 Be7 $19) 10... f5!? 11. exf5 (11. cxd4 fxe4! (11... exd4 12. e5! { lets White off of the hook somewhat - opening up the
center completely favors Black, who has the safer king and better development. }) 12. Nxe5 (12. dxe4 exd4 13. a3 O-O-O $19 { and What's position will be
horrible after Black brings his rook to the f-file. }) 12... Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Ncxe5 14. dxe5 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 exd3 $19) 11... Bxf5 12. cxd4 exd4 13. Nf4 O-O-O { and Black face a serious dilemma - castle and drop the h-pawn after ...Nxf4 or
leave the king in the center and deal with problems down the d-file, e.g. } 14. Nxg6 (14. O-O Nxf4 15. Bxf4 Bxh3 $19) 14... Re8+! 15. Kf1 Bxg6 $19 *


