1. g4 d5 2. Bg2 Bxg4 3. c4 c6! { [%cal Gd1b3,Gc4d5] } (3... dxc4!? 4. Bxb7 Nd7 { has been recommended in more than one source and certainly isn't bad, especially if White takes the exchange. But if they don't, e.g. } 5. Na3!? { , then I'm not sure it's better than the main line. }) 4. cxd5 (4. Qb3 Nf6 (4... Qd7!? 5. cxd5 Nf6 6. Nc3 cxd5 7. Nxd5 Nc6) (4... e6 5. cxd5 exd5! (5... cxd5?? 6. Qa4+ $18)) 5. Nc3 (5. Qxb7 Nbd7 6. Qxc6 (6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Nc3 (7. Bxd5? Rb8 8. Qc6 Rc8 $19) 7... e6 { transposes back to 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Qb3. }) 6... Rc8 7. Qb5 e5! { is exceedingly
dangerous for White, and } 8. Bxd5 Rc5 $19 { explicitly loses, as the c-pawn is
actually pinned to the c1-bishop. }) 5... e6 6. Qxb7 Nbd7 7. cxd5 (7. d4 Rb8 (7... Rc8 { is also good. }) 8. Qxc6 Rc8 9. Qa6 Rxc4 10. h3 (10. e3 Bb4 11. Bd2 Qc7 12. Rc1 O-O 13. a3 Bd6 14. Nge2 Rc6) 10... Bh5 11. Nf3 Bb4 12. O-O (12. Bd2? Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Rxd4) 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 O-O $17) 7... cxd5 { transposes back
to 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Qb3. }) 4... cxd5 5. Qb3 Nf6! 6. Qxb7 (6. Nc3 e6 7. Qxb7 Nbd7 { transposes. }) 6... Nbd7 7. Nc3 (7. d4? Rb8 8. Qa6 (8. Qxa7 Qc8! $19 { [%cal Gc8c1,Gb8a8] }) 8... e5! { [%csl Gf8] } 9. e3 Bb4+ 10. Nc3 O-O 11. dxe5 Nc5! 12. Qf1 d4! 13. exd4 Qxd4 14. Bf3 Bxc3+ { of J.Lenz-J.Ardila Barrera,
Correspondence 2016, was a very clean kill. }) 7... e6 8. d4 (8. Nb5 Rc8 9. Qxa7 (9. Nxa7 { I.Ariston-I.Laczay, Correspondence 2006 } 9... Rb8 $146 { and I think the
knight is never coming back out, e.g. } 10. Qc6 (10. Qa6 Rb6 11. Qa4 (11. Qc8 Qxc8 12. Nxc8 Ra6 $19) 11... Qa8! $19 { [%cal Gb6b7] }) 10... Qa5 $19) 9... Ne4!? { Stockfish
digs this move. Not super intuitive, but when you delve into the variations,
it makes a ton of sense. White sort of has to capture, but after he does, his
g1-knight can no longer enter the game, and Black is ready for ...Qh4 and ...
Bc5. } { [%cal Gf8c5,Gc5f2] } (9... Bc5 10. Qa4 O-O 11. d4 { has been played more, but also feels like
you're allowing White to put up more resistance. }) 10. Bxe4 dxe4 { [%cal Gf8c5,Gd8h4] } 11. Qd4 Bf5 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. Qxd6 Rc2 { Honestly, I don't know how White held either game
that reached this position. } { [%cal Gd8c8] }) (8. Nf3 Rb8 9. Qxa7? Nc5! { and White is
basically powerless to stop ...Ra8, trapping the queen. }) 8... Rb8 9. Qa6 (9. Qxa7 { H.Grob -F.Wegmuller, Correspondence 1960 (The man himself!) } 9... Qc8! $146 { [%cal Gb8a8] } 10. Qa4 Bb4 11. Bd2 (11. Qc2 Bf5 $19) 11... Qc4! { [%cal Gb4c3] } 12. Qc2 Qxd4 { and Black
bags his pawn back with a large positional advantage, e.g. } 13. h3 Bf5 14. Nf3 Qb6 15. Qd1 O-O 16. O-O e5 { -/+/-+ and Black dominates the central real estate. }) 9... Bb4 { [%cal Gf6e4,Gd8c7] } 10. Nf3 (10. Qxa7 { once again loses instantly to } 10... Qc8! { , with
the dual threats of ...Ra8 and smashing on c3. }) 10... Ne4 11. a3 (11. Bd2 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nxd2 13. Kxd2 Qf6 $19) 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 O-O (12... Qc7 13. O-O O-O { transposes. }) 13. O-O Qc7 14. Qd3 { This position has been reached in a few
correspondence games, and White has lost all of them. I've pasted a few below,
as one player in particular seems to really believe in White's chances here.
Bottom line is that White can't keep the c3-pawn, and will still have big
positional problems after that as well. Less active pieces, a looser kingside,
and a weak a3-pawn. } { [%cal Gf8c8,Gb8b3] } 14... Rfc8 (14... Rb3 15. Bd2 Ndf6 16. Ne5 Bf5 17. Qe3 Nxd2 18. Qxd2 Rc8 19. Rac1 Ne4 20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. f3 Bh3 22. Rfd1 f6 23. Ng4 exf3 24. exf3 Rxc3 25. Rxc3 Qxc3 26. Qe2 h5 27. Nf2 Bf5 28. d5 e5 29. a4 Qb3 30. d6 Rc2 31. Rd2 Rxd2 32. Qxd2 Qxa4 33. Qd5+ Kh7 34. f4 a5 35. fxe5 Qa1+ 36. Nd1 fxe5 37. d7 Bxd7 38. Qxd7 Qd4+ 39. Qxd4 exd4 40. Nb2 g5 41. Kf1 g4 42. Kf2 h4 43. Ke2 h3 44. Kf1 Kg6 45. Na4 d3 46. Nc3 g3 47. Nd1 gxh2 48. Nf2 a4 49. Ke1 a3 50. Kd2 a2 { 0-1 (50) Kaytazki,L (1396)-Tsenkov,L (2260) ICCF 2018 }) 15. Ng5 Nef6 16. e4 Rb3 17. f3 Rxc3 18. Qe2 Bh5 19. Bd2 Rc4 20. e5 Ne4 21. Nxe4 dxe4 22. Qe3 exf3 23. Bxf3 Bxf3 24. Rxf3 Qb6 25. Rf4 Nf8 26. Bb4 Ng6 27. Re4 a5 28. Bc5 Qb2 29. Rf1 Qb7 30. Re1 Qd5 31. Qe2 Rb8 32. Rg4 Rb3 33. Qe4 Qxe4 34. Rgxe4 Rcc3 35. Rf1 h5 36. Bd6 Rh3 37. d5 Nh4 38. dxe6 fxe6 39. Re2 a4 40. Kh1 Kh7 41. Rg1 Nf3 42. Rd1 g5 43. Bc5 h4 44. Bg1 Rxa3 45. Kg2 g4 46. Rc1 Rb3 47. Rf2 Kg6 48. Rc4 Nxg1 49. Kxg1 g3 50. hxg3 Rbxg3+ 51. Rg2 a3 52. Rb4 a2 53. Ra4 a1=Q+ 54. Rxa1 Rxg2+ 55. Kxg2 Re3 56. Ra5 Kf5 57. Rb5 Rxe5 58. Rb3 { 0-1 (58) Kaytazki,L (1408)
-Eijkenboom,R ICCF 2018 } *


