1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8) 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 { [%cal Ga4c6,Gf3e5] } 6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O { [%cal Ga2a4,Gh2h3] } 8. h3!? { Nepo unsurprisingly shoots for an Anti-Marshall. } (8. c3 d5 { [%csl Ge5] } 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 { [%cal Ge5d5] } 11... c6 { The main tabiya of the dreaded Marshall Attack. Once a
feared attacking weapon, nowadays this variation is mostly considered a very
reliable drawing weapon because of how far computer engines can push out the
analysis, for both the attacker and defender. Many positions simplify into
opposite-colored bishop scenarios, which are notoriously drawish as well. } 12. d4 (12. d3!? Bd6 13. Re1 { [%cal Gc8f5] } 13... Bf5 { Black takes aim at the weak pawn on d3 right
away. } (13... Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 15. Re4 { reveals the main subtlety behind 12.d3 -
with the rook on e4 protected, Black can no longer play ...g5 and rely on the
double attack with ...Qf5 if the pawn is captured. }) 14. Qf3 Qh4 (14... Qf6!? 15. Nd2 Qg6 { V.Anand-P.Svidler, Khanty-Mansiysk 2014. The thread of ...Bg4,
the weakness on d3, and White's bad queenside development give Black great
play for the pawn. }) 15. g3 Qh3 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Qxd5 Rad8 18. Qg2 Qh5 19. Be3 { A.Shirov-D.Jakovenko, Russian Team Championships 2008. Due to White's lagging
development, weak light squares (especially on the kingside) and Black's two
bishops, the second player has had good compensation after any of the main
moves here, those being 19...Bh3, 19...Bxd3, and 19...b4. }) 12... Bd6 13. Re1 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 { [%cal Ge1e4,Gc1e3,Rc8g4] } 15. Re4 (15. Be3 Bg4 16. Qd3 Rae8 (16... f5!? { also looks
interesting and was played by the man himself in V.Ivanchuk-M.Carlsen, Leuven
rapid 2017 } { [%cal Rf5f4] }) 17. Nd2 Re6 18. a4 Qh5 { has been played in a huge number of games
and is very similar to E.Safarli-E.Tomashevsky, Aeroflot open 2012 (see below),
the only real difference being a queen on d3 instead of f1. }) (15. Qf3 Bg4 16. Qg2 Qh5 17. Be3 Rae8 18. Nd2 Re6 19. a4 Rfe8 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ra7 h6 $44 { E.Safarli-E.Tomashevsky, Aeroflot Open 2012 }) 15... g5! { [%cal Rf7f5,Rf5f4] } 16. Qf1 (16. Bxg5?? Qf5 $19 { [%csl Ge4,Gg5] }) 16... Qh5 $44) (8. a4 { is the other main option to avoid the Marshall
Attack. }) 8... Na5!? { Already a shock very early in game 1! A super rare but
very interesting idea, offering up the e-pawn again in pseudo-Marshall style. } (8... d5?! 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 { is the point of White's 8th -
this pawn sacrifice idea is quite a bit less appealing with the pawns on h3
and c2. }) (8... Bb7 9. d3 { has historically been the most popular and now: } 9... d6 { [%csl Yb3][%cal Bc6a5,Bc7c5] } (9... d5!? { is also possible and after } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxe5 { both 11...
Nd4!? and 11...Nxe5 are possible and seem very reasonable for Black. }) 10. a3 Na5 11. Ba2 c5 12. Nc3 (12. Nbd2 { is also very popular and reasonable. }) 12... Nc6 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Qc7 15. c3 Nb8 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. d4 { of C.Lutz-R.
Kasimdzhanov, Bundesliga 2003, is one logical and possible line of play. }) (8... d6 9. c3 { is actually just a transposition to the main line of the entire
Closed Ruy, except that White has avoided the Marshall. }) 9. Nxe5 { Ian took on
e5 quite quickly, perhaps because he had looked at this line himself, or
perhaps because he thought White was forced to do so to get anything. } 9... Nxb3 10. axb3 Bb7 11. d3 d5! { Again, this gives the game a slight "Marshall"
character. The black pieces spring to life and the game opens up for the two
bishops. } 12. exd5 (12. Nc3 dxe4 13. dxe4 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 (15. Bf4) 15... Bxe4 16. c3 Bd6 $15 { [%csl Ge4,Gd6] }) 12... Qxd5 { [%cal Gd5g2] } 13. Qf3 (13. Nf3 Rae8 14. Nc3 Qf5 $44) 13... Bd6 { [%cal Gd5e5,Gb7f3] } 14. Kf1! { This surprising move, avoiding some tricks with ...
Qxe5, was also played quite quickly, leading me to believe that team Nepo had
also seen this before. } (14. Nc3?? Qxe5! 15. Rxe5 (15. Qxb7?? Qxe1#) 15... Bxf3) (14. Qxd5 Nxd5 { [%cal Rd5b4,Rf8e8] } 15. Bd2 Ne7! $44 { [%csl Gc2,Gb3,Yg2][%cal Ge7f5,Gf5d4,Gd4b3,Gd4c2,Yb7g2,Yf5h4,Yh4g2] }) 14... Rfb8! (14... Rab8? 15. Qxd5 Bxd5 (15... Nxd5 16. Nd7 $18) 16. Rxa6 $18) 15. Qxd5 Nxd5 16. Bd2 c5! { Carlsen had used just 7 minutes to reach this position, which is indicative
that he was still in his preparation. } { [%cal Gd3d4,Ge5d3] } 17. Nf3 { Ian's first long think - it'd
be interesting to hear what he thought of the less clumsy (in my opinion) } (17. Nc3 Nb4 18. Rac1 { with a complicated fight ahead. }) 17... Rd8 18. Nc3 Nb4 19. Rec1 Rac8 $44 { Black has very reasonable long term compensation in this
position - the two bishops, the Nb4 putting lots of pressure on White's
queenside pawn weaknesses, and the difference in piece activity overall. } { [%csl Gb4,Gd6,Gb7,Ya1,Yc1,Yd2,Rc2] } 20. Ne2 Nc6 21. Be3 Ne7 22. Bf4 Bxf3 23. gxf3 Bxf4 24. Nxf4 Rc6 25. Re1 Nf5 26. c3 Nh4 27. Re3 Kf8 28. Ng2 Nf5 29. Re5 g6 30. Ne1 Ng7 31. Re4 f5 32. Re3 Ne6 33. Ng2 b4 34. Ke2 Rb8 35. Kd2 bxc3+ 36. bxc3 Rxb3 37. Kc2 Rb7 38. h4 Kf7 39. Ree1 Kf6 40. Ne3 Rd7 41. Nc4 Re7 42. Ne5 Rd6 43. Nc4 Rc6 44. Ne5 Rd6 45. Nc4 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


