1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 { [%cal Gd5c4] } 4... Be7 (4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 (5... Bd6)) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 { Releasing the
central tension and working towards either ...b5 or ...c5 is the most popular
strategy for dealing with the Catalan nowadays. } (6... c6 { It's also totally
fine to enter what some call the "Closed Catalan" with this move. Black will
usually slowly develop with ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Na6/d7, and then look to use
either ...c5 or ...e5 as an equalizing break. For example, a popular option is } 7. Qc2 (7. Nc3 { or 7.b3 are also major options }) 7... b6 8. Nbd2 Bb7 9. e4 Na6 (9... dxe4?! { is common (especially at lower levels), but releasing the
tension in this way is probably just bad and has scored absolutely terribly,
for instance } 10. Nxe4 Nbd7 11. Rd1 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qe2 Qc7 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 (15. Ne5 { of S.Sethuraman-R.Muradyan, Yerevan 2018 is also powerful }) 15... Qxd6 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. c5 $16 { E.Ghaem Maghani-S.Karami, Khomeyn Aftab Cup
2017. Black is under a lot of pressure, and the stark difference between the
minor pieces is telling. }) 10. a3 c5 $132 { H.Nakamura-Y.Yu, Gibraltar 2017 }) 7. Qc2 { This has taken over relative to the other main idea 7.Ne5, I think
perhaps because the positions are less linear and there's simply more room to
try and find new ideas. } (7. Ne5 Nc6! { turns out to be a tough nut to crack. }) 7... b5!? { Already a surprise - a big deviation compared to the almost
ubiquitous 7...a6. } (7... a6 { has been a battleground ever since Kramnik
rejuvenated the Catalan in the early 2000s. White has to decide whether or not
to allow ...b5 now, e.g.: } 8. a4 (8. Qxc4 b5 { [%cal Gc8b7] } 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gd2a5] } 10... Be4 11. Qc1 { was the main try in this position for a long time, though recently people have
shifted to 8.a4. That may change! }) 8... Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 { [%cal Gc1f4,Gf4g5] }) 8. Ne5!? { Carlsen
likely played this to avoid the hot 8.a4 Bb7!? idea in the notes below. } { [%cal Gg2a8] } (8. a4 { is the most common move and Avrukh's recommendation in the "GM Repertoire"
series, but at the time 8...Bb7 had not been played yet. } 8... Bb7!? { Not an easy
move to stumble upon! } (8... b4 9. Nfd2! { [%cal Gg2a8] } 9... c6 (9... Nd5!? { is also possible
and after } 10. Nxc4 c5 11. dxc5 Ba6! { of L.Ding-M.Carlsen, Zagreb 2019 was
an idea Carlsen found himself preparing for previous WC matches. } { [%cal Bb8d7,Ba8c8] }) 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Be3 Qh5 13. Nbd2 Ng4 14. Nf3 Nxe3 15. Nxe3 a5 16. Nd4 { A.Grischuk-H.Nakamura, Moscow 2019 is probably less comfortable for Black than
8...Bb7. Or at least practically more risky. }) 9. axb5 a6 10. Nc3 (10. bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qxc4 Bd5 12. Qd3 Nb4 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Qd1 { of F.Berkes-A.Grischuk,
European Championships 2021. Black seems to have reasonable compensation after
both 14...Na2!? and 14...c5. } { [%cal Gb4a2,Gc7c5] }) 10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 Bd5 $13 { B.Gelfand-V.Fedoseev, online blitz 2021 }) 8... c6 (8... Nd5 { Black can also start with this move and play can possibly transpose to the game after 9.a4 f6, etc, but White also gets the extra option of } 9. b3!? $13 { as well. }) 9. a4 { [%cal Ge5c6] } (9. Nxc6 Nxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 { is not all that impressive for White, since Black gets to keep his
queenside pawn phalanx intact after } { [%cal Gb8b5] } 11. a4 a6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Nc3 Bd7 { ,etc. }) 9... Nd5 { There is really no other way to deal with the dual threats of
axb5 and Nxc6. Black installs the knight in d5, blunting the pressure along
the long diagonal and preparing to boot the knight with ...f6. As we'll see in
the game, this also stops Black's knight from getting frozen on the f6-square
for a while after White plays e4 - instead the second gets to install it on d3
with tempo. After this, Ian used most of his first hour between now and 13...
Nd3, suggesting perhaps he wasn't totally ready for Magnus' 8.Ne5 idea. } { [%cal Ga4b5,Ge5c6] } 10. Nc3 { [%cal Gb5b4] } 10... f6 { Black boots the knight to carve out the d7-square for his queen, which
will protect his shaky queenside pawn structure. } (10... b4!? { is the only
other logical way I could think of to keep Black's shaky queenside mostly
together, and indeed, I'm not certain he's much worse at all after } 11. Ne4 Ba6 12. Nxc4 Nd7 13. b3 Rc8 { of E.Goltseva-S.Tereladze, online blitz 2021 }) 11. Nf3 Qd7 (11... b4 12. Ne4 Ba6 $13 { was again worth considering. }) 12. e4 Nb4 13. Qe2 Nd3 14. e5! { Carlsen's first significant think, and he finds a nice
multipurpose move! White opens the long diagonal and the game in general,
which is logical given Black's laggy development and shaky position position
overall. Carlsen also might have found ...b4 awkward to meet, and now he has
the very active Ne4 in response. } 14... Bb7 (14... f5 { was also logical, e.g. } 15. axb5 Bb7! (15... cxb5? 16. d5! exd5 17. Ne1! Nxc1 18. Rxc1 Bb7 19. e6 Qd6 20. Rd1 { leaves Black under heaps of pressure! }) 16. b3!? { with a
complicated mess. }) 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Ne4 Na6 { [%cal Gc1e3] } 17. Ne5?! { Carlsen starts to go
astray here. } (17. Nxf6+ gxf6 { [%cal Yf3e5,Yf6e5] } 18. Bh6 Rf7 19. Ne1!? $44) (17. Be3 $44 { [%cal Gb2b3] }) 17... Bxe5! (17... Nxe5? 18. dxe5 Bxe5 19. Ng5 $18 { is a bloodbath. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gg2e4,Ge2h5] }) 18. dxe5 Nac5 19. Nd6 Nb3 { [%cal Gb3c1,Gd3c1,Gb3a1] } (19... Nxa4!?) 20. Rb1? { Again a slip. It seems natural to
me that given that an exchange is lost either way, that White should keep the
dark-squared instead. } (20. Be3! Nxa1 21. Rxa1 Nxe5 (21... bxa4 22. Be4 Nxe5 23. Qh5 (23. Bc5) 23... Ng6 24. Bc5 $44) 22. Bc5 Nd3 23. Nxb7 { [%cal Gd3c5,Gb7c5] } 23... Qxb7 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 25. axb5 Qxb5 26. Qxe6+ Kh8 27. Rxa7) 20... Nbxc1 21. Rbxc1 Nxc1 22. Rxc1 Rab8 $17 23. Rd1 Ba8 24. Be4 c3 25. Qc2 g6 26. bxc3 bxa4 27. Qxa4 Rfd8 28. Ra1 c5 29. Qc4 Bxe4 30. Nxe4 Kh8 31. Nd6 Rb6 32. Qxc5 Rdb8 33. Kg2 a6 34. Kh3 Rc6 35. Qd4 Kg8 36. c4 Qc7 37. Qg4 Rxd6 38. exd6 Qxd6 39. c5 Qxc5 40. Qxe6+ Kg7 41. Rxa6 Rf8 42. f4 Qf5+ 43. Qxf5 Rxf5 44. Ra7+ Kg8 45. Kg4 Rb5 46. Re7 Ra5 47. Re5 Ra7 48. h4 Kg7 49. h5 Kh6 50. Kh4 Ra1 51. g4 Rh1+ 52. Kg3 gxh5 53. Re6+ Kg7 54. g5 Rg1+ 55. Kf2 Ra1 56. Rh6 Ra4 57. Kf3 Ra3+ 58. Kf2 Ra4 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


