1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O { Once again we see Magnus offering up a Marshall Gambit... } 8. a4!? { And once
again Nepo (probably rightfully) refuses! } 8... Bb7 (8... b4 { is also an important
option. }) 9. d3 { White must be content with d3-based strategies. } (9. c3 { is pretty nicely met by } 9... d5! { It appears as though the insertion of a4 and
Bb7 favors Black in the Marshall-style positions, unsurprisingly. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. Nxe5?? Nxe5 14. Rxe5 { [%csl Ga8] } 14... Nf4! { and Black
is actually already winning, e.g. } { [%csl Gg2] } 15. f3 Nd3 16. Re2 Bc5+ 17. Kf1 Qh4 $19 { and it all falls apart. }) 9... d6 { Black protects the e-pawn, giving the
option of ...Na5 and ...c5. } { [%cal Gc6a5] } 10. Nbd2 Re8!? { The fourth most popular move -
against Nepo is content to play the classical main lines and Magnus deviates
first with a playable alternative.The game takes on a slower, Zaitsev-like
character now. Black slowly organizes ...d5 and White can try many different
ideas - building up on the kingside by trying to bring a knight to f5, or
playing on the queenside with the c4-break for instance. } (10... Na5 11. Ba2 c5 12. Nf1 { [%cal Gb5b4,Gb5a4,Gd8c7] } 12... Bc8!? { M.Matlakov-A.Karpov, Moscow blitz 2021 }) (10... Nd7 11. c3 Nc5 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Bc2 b4 15. d4 bxc3 16. bxc3 Nd7 17. Nf1 Qa1 { P.Svidler-D.Swiercz, Sinquefield Cup 2021 }) 11. Nf1 h6 12. Bd2 { [%cal Gd2a5] } 12... Bf8 { [%cal Gd6d5] } 13. Ne3 { [%cal Ge3f5,Ge3d5] } 13... Ne7 14. c4 { [%cal Gb5a4] } 14... bxc4 15. Nxc4 { [%cal Rc4e5] } 15... Nc6 (15... Ng6 16. Na5 { [%csl Gc6,Gc7] } 16... Bc8 17. Nc6 Qd7 18. Rc1 $14) 16. Rc1 { [%cal Yc4a5] } 16... a5 { The Norwegian's first long think of the game, around 15 minutes. I was
a little surprised by this move (what do I know, but doesn't it look weak),
but upon analysis, Magnus was unsurprisingly proven correct by practice and
engines. Allowing Na5 was almost certainly worse! } 17. Bc3 { [%cal Gd6d5] } 17... Bc8! 18. d4 exd4 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Qxd4 Be6 21. h3 { Nepo tries to usefully improve before the ..
.d5-break hits. } (21. Nxa5? c5! 22. Qd2 Bxb3 { and both e4 and a4 are
hanging - Black is very active now! }) 21... c6! { White can't really stop ...
d5, and after this equalizing break, Nepo had very little to speak of. } 22. Bc2 d5! 23. e5 dxc4 24. Qxd8 Rexd8 25. exf6 Bb4 26. fxg7 Bxc3 27. bxc3 Kxg7 { [%csl Gc6,Gc4] } 28. Kf1 Rab8 29. Rb1 Kf6 30. Rxb8 Rxb8 31. Rb1 Rxb1+ 32. Bxb1 Ke5 33. Ke2 f5 34. Bc2 f4 35. Bb1 c5 36. Bc2 Bd7 37. f3 Kf6 38. h4 Ke5 39. Kf2 Kf6 40. Ke2 Ke5 41. Kf2 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


