1. e4 { [%eval 0.0] } { As I guessed, Carlsen continues to probe as White and does not repeat his experiment in the Catalan. } { [%clk 1:59:57] } 1... e5 { [%eval 0.12] [%clk 1:59:53] } 2. Nf3 { [%eval 0.37] [%clk 1:59:46] } 2... Nf6 { [%eval 0.51] } { The Russian plays the Russian. *sad trombone* } { [%clk 1:59:45] } 3. Nxe5 { [%eval 0.31] [%clk 1:59:28] } 3... d6 { [%eval 0.37] [%clk 1:59:39] } (3... Nxe4?! { is probably unplayable but not as easy to refute as many make it to be! } 4. Qe2 Qe7 (4... d5 5. d3 Nf6?? 6. Nc6+ $18) 5. Qxe4 d6 { [%cal Ge7e4] } 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Bb5 (8. Nc3! Qxe5 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Nb5! Bb4+ 11. Bd2 (11. c3?! Ba5 $13) 11... Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 { [%cal Ge8d8] } 12... Kd8 13. Re1 $16) 8... Bd7 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10. Bf4 Qb4 (10... g5!?)) 4. Nf3 { [%eval 0.29] [%clk 1:59:24] } 4... Nxe4 { [%eval 0.25] [%clk 1:59:33] } 5. d4 { [%eval 0.13] [%clk 1:59:18] } (5. Nc3!? Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 { has historically been the other main line. I would expect to see Carlsen try this variation if he decides to push his king pawn again and test Nepo's Petroff. }) 5... d5 { [%eval 0.58] [%clk 1:59:10] } 6. Bd3 { [%eval 0.28] [%clk 1:59:02] } 6... Bd6!? { [%eval 0.23] [%clk 1:59:04] } (6... Nc6 { has been more popular historically, but when Caruana caused interest in the Petroff to boom again a few years back, he focused on 6...Bd6!? as well, which nowadays is probably considered the main line. }) 7. O-O { [%eval 0.28] [%clk 1:58:52] } 7... O-O { [%eval 0.33] [%clk 1:58:58] } 8. c4 { [%eval 0.37] [%clk 1:57:49] } 8... c6 { [%eval 0.37] [%clk 1:56:36] } 9. Re1 { [%eval 0.45] } { This is a main theme in the Petroff - White looks to increase the tension against this far-posted knight and prove that it's actually worse here than on f6. } { [%csl Ye4] [%clk 1:57:38] } 9... Bf5 { [%eval 0.45] [%clk 1:53:09] } 10. Qb3 { [%eval 0.77] [%cal Gb3d5,Gb3b7] [%clk 1:56:36] } 10... Qd7 { [%eval 0.43] [%clk 1:52:17] } (10... Qb6? { is an instructive mistake, as after } 11. Qc2! { Black faces both problems with the e4/f5 constellation of pieces and with the threat of a fork with c5. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc4c5,Gd3f5] } 11... Qc7 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. Bxf5 $18) (10... Na6 11. Qxb7?? (11. Nc3 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 b5 14. Bf1 Nc7) 11... Nb4! $19 { [%cal Rb4d3,Rb4c2,Yd8f6,Yf8b8] }) 11. Nc3 { [%eval 0.41] [%clk 1:55:08] } 11... Nxc3 { [%eval 0.22] [%clk 1:51:55] } 12. Bxf5 { [%eval 0.21] [%clk 1:55:00] } (12. Qxc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 dxc4 14. Qxc4 $15) 12... Qxf5 { [%eval 0.28] [%clk 1:51:50] } 13. bxc3 { [%eval 0.24] [%clk 1:54:49] } (13. Qxb7 { is playable but tricky, as White's queen never makes it back out! } 13... Ne4 14. Qxa8 Qd7 { [%cal Rb8a6] } 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rxe4 $7 Nc6 17. Qxf8+ Kxf8 18. Re2 $13 { M.Ragger-T.Nguyen, Bundesliga 2021 }) 13... b6 { [%eval 0.14] [%clk 1:49:17] } 14. cxd5 { [%eval 0.14] [%clk 1:54:39] } 14... cxd5 { [%eval 0.37] [%csl Yc4][%cal Yc6a5,Ya5c4,Yb8c6] [%clk 1:48:47] } 15. Qb5! { [%eval 0.26] [%clk 1:54:28] } 15... Qd7 { [%eval 0.2] [%clk 1:48:30] } (15... Nd7? 16. Qc6 { [%csl Rd6] } 16... Bb8 17. Ba3 (17. Qxa8?? Bxh2+!) 17... Rd8 18. Be7 $18) 16. a4! { [%eval 0.12] } { White leaves the tension, as a pawn on b5 would be an upgrade, opening the a-file and exposing a backward pawn on a7. } { [%clk 1:53:36] } 16... Qxb5 { [%eval 0.15] [%clk 1:47:52] } 17. axb5 { [%eval 0.18] [%csl Ga7][%cal Ga1a7] [%clk 1:53:33] } 17... a5! { [%eval 0.14] } { It's probably best to push here immediately, forcing White to either take and enter a drawish ending or accept a passed a-pawn. } { [%clk 1:47:41] } 18. Nh4!? $146 { [%eval -0.08] } { White threatens to win immediately with Nf5, but also long term wants to put the knight on e3. } { [%clk 1:53:26] } (18. bxa6 Nxa6 19. Ba3 Bxa3 20. Rxa3 Nc7 21. Rb3 b5 22. Rc1 Ra2 23. Ne5 g5 24. Nd3 Re8 25. Rb2 Rxb2 26. Nxb2 Ra8 27. Kf1 Kf8 28. Nd3 { Miettinen, Kristo S. - Leonard, Andrew, 1/2-1/2, BITNY/A 2021 (USA), https://lichess.org/Qx3GGzG6 }) 18... g6 { [%eval -0.15] [%clk 1:42:12] } 19. g4! { [%eva