1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Qb6 8. Qd2 { The Najdorf Poisoned Pawn variation - one of the craziest and most notorious
opening lines in all of chess, made famous by the Fischer-Spassky match in
1972. White offers the b2-pawn to sideline the Black queen and grab a quick
lead in development. Nowadays this position is hotly debated mostly between
top GMs who revel in complications and correspondence players. } (8. Qd3!? { is also possible and has it's own nuances, the main line being } 8... Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. f5 $13 Be7 (10... Qa5!?) 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Be2 Qa5 13. Bd2 Qc7 14. g4!? h6 15. Qh3 $13 { when we use the fact that White played Qd3 to good effect! } { [%cal Bh3h8] }) 8... Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 { [%csl Ra3] } 10. e5 { This variation (at least this is my impression)
became popular (again) back in the 2005/2006 time frame after a game by Igor
Nataf and then a few Radjabov wins against Anand and Karjakin. No surprise, as
Nataf is Radjabov's coach - they must have done some work on this position and
put it to good use. Later correspondence players became very interested in the
main position around move 15 and hundreds of games were played in just a few
years time. } (10. Be2) 10... h6 { Black actually really needs to insert ...h6,
for example: } (10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Nfd7 (11... h6) 12. Ne4 Qxa2 (12... h6) 13. Rd1 Qd5 14. Qe3 Qxe5 (14... Bc5? 15. Nxe6! Bb4+ (15... Qxe6 16. Qxc5 $18 { M.Gustain-R.Sand,
German Leagues 2010 }) (15... Bxe3 16. Nc7+ Kf8 17. Rxd5 Bxg5 18. Nxg5) 16. c3 Qxe6 17. cxb4 $18 O-O 18. Rd6! Qa2 19. Be2 Qb1+ 20. Kf2 Qxh1 21. Bh6!! { [%cal Gh6g7,Ge3g5] } 21... Qxh2 22. Qg5 g6 23. Bxf8 Kxf8 (23... Nxf8 24. Nf6+ Kg7 25. Nh5+ Kg8 26. Rd8 Nd7 27. Qe7 gxh5 28. Qg5+ Kh8 29. Bxh5 $18) 24. e6 fxe6 25. Rxe6 Nc6 26. Nd6 { 1-0 M.Yilmazyerli-D.Benidze, Izmir 2016 }) 15. Be2 Bc5 16. O-O O-O 17. Bf4 Qd5 18. c4 Qc6 19. Bd6! Qb6 (19... Bxd4 20. Rxd4 Re8 21. Rxf7!? Kxf7 22. Bh5+ g6 23. Qh6! $18) 20. Bxf8 Nxf8 21. Bh5 f6 22. Nxf6+! $18 { A.Rotella-A.Oleksak, Correspondence 2010 }) 11. Bh4 dxe5 12. fxe5 { [%cal Gg7g5] } 12... Nfd7 13. Ne4 Qxa2 (13... Nxe5?? 14. Nb5! $18) 14. Rd1 Qd5 15. Qe3 Qxe5 { [%cal Gh4g3,Gf1e2] } (15... Bc5 16. Nxe6 Bb4+ 17. c3 Qxe6 18. cxb4 O-O 19. Rd6 Qa2 20. Be2 Qb1+ 21. Kf2 Qxb4 22. Rhd1 Nc6 23. Rxd7 Bxd7 24. Rxd7 Nxe5 25. Be7 Qa5) 16. c3!? { In a position
that has been played hundreds of times now, an "OTB novelty". I could only dig
up 8 games, and they were all from the correspondence realm. White's 18th is
actually completely new, and no surprise there! } (16. Be2 Bc5 17. Bg3 (17. O-O Nc6 18. c3 { and Black gets to castle and is probably better, e.g. } 18... O-O 19. Bg3 Qd5 { and the consolidating ...e5 is coming. }) 17... Qd5 18. c4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qa5+ 20. Rd2 O-O 21. Bd6 f5 22. Bxf8 Nxf8 23. Nd6 Nbd7 $13 { A.Giri-M.Vachier
Lagrave, Paris (rapid) 2019 }) 16... Bc5 (16... Be7!? { this is Stockfish's
preference, but man how do you find this move after being surprised by 16.c3? }) 17. Bg3 Qd5 (17... Bxd4 18. Rxd4 Qa5 19. Nd6+ $18 { and
White's attack is no doubt terminal. }) 18. Bc4!! $146 { WHAT!? } (18. Bd6!? Bxd6 19. Nb5 Qxd1+ 20. Kxd1 Be5 (20... axb5!? $146 21. Nxd6+ Ke7 22. Nf5+ Kf8 { and I honestly have no idea what's going on! }) 21. Nbd6+ Ke7 22. Nc4 { [%cal Gb8c6] } 22... Rd8 (22... Nc6 $13 { A.Oleksak-B.Panyushkin, Correspondence 2010 }) 23. Kc2 $13 { and White eventually won in C.Beveridge-L.Milde, Correspondence 2013 }) 18... Qxc4 19. Bd6! { White is 3 pawns and a piece down but Black is very behind
in development and can't castle. MVL finds a good way to shed some material
and untangle his mess of pieces. } 19... Nf6! (19... Bxd4!? 20. Rxd4 Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b1] } 21. Qg3!? (21. O-O $13) 21... Qb1+ 22. Kf2 Qxh1 23. Qxg7 Rf8 24. Bc5! Nxc5 25. Rd8+! Kxd8 26. Qxf8+ Kc7 27. Qd6#) (19... f5 20. Nxc5 Nxc5 (20... Kf7!) 21. Nxf5 $40 { [%cal Gf5g7] }) (19... Nc6 20. Bxc5) 20. Nxc5 Nd5 (20... Nbd7 21. Nf5 Rg8 22. Be7! $18 { THUNK! }) 21. Qe5 Rg8 { [%csl Gc5,Gd6,Ge5,Gd4] } (21... Qxc3+ 22. Kf2 Qb2+ 23. Kg3 Nf6 24. Rhf1 $40) 22. Ndxe6! fxe6 23. Nxe6 Qxc3+ (23... Nf6!? 24. Nc7+?? Kf7! $19) 24. Qxc3 Nxc3 25. Nc7+ Kf7 26. Rd3 { [%csl Gc3,Ga8] } 26... Ne4 (26... Ra7! 27. O-O+ Kg6 28. Rxc3 Kh7 29. Nd5) 27. O-O+! { White casually completes his development and
castles on move 27. } (27. Nxa8 Nxd6 28. Rxd6 Ke7 $13 { Howell pointed out in
the press conference that Black's king might be happier on the queenside with
his majority. }) 27... Kg6 28. Nxa8 Nc6 29. Nb6 $16 { I think it's pretty clear
that White has navigated the opening phase more accurately and has some pull,
it's just a question of how much and whether or not it's good enough to win.
For now the exchange and White's activity is more relevant than the two
connected passers on the queenside. } 29... Rd8 30. Nxc8 Rxc8 31. Ba3 (31. Re1 { is preferred by Stockfish and was definitely an interesting option. } 31... Nf6 32. Rb1 b5 33. Rc1 Ne7 34. Rxc8 Nxc8 35. Bc5 { - it's hard for Black to hold the
queenside, and R+B vs 2N with 2-pawns on the queenside is probably a lot
easier to win for White than the positions in the game. }) 31... Rc7 32. Rf4 Nf6 33. Bb2 Ne7 34. Bxf6 (34. Rd6 Nc8) 34... gxf6 35. h4 { No one seems to be in
favor of this move after the fact, the problem being that it's hard to keep
the h-pawns on the board now, which eases Black's defensive task. } (35. h3!?) 35... h5 { Black probably correctly puts a stop to White's ambitious expansion
on the kingside. In many lines later if White played g4 this duo was dangerous.
Now White also needs to worry somewhat about the knight slamming onto g4
instead. } 36. Rg3+ Kf7 37. Rg5! { [%cal Gf4f7,Gg5h5] } 37... Rc1+ (37... Ng6 38. Rxh5 Nxf4 (38... Rc1+ 39. Rf1 Rxf1+ 40. Kxf1 Kg7 41. g3 $18) 39. Rh7+ { [%cal Gh7c7] } 39... Kg6 40. Rxc7 b5 41. Rc6 a5 42. Rc5 $18) 38. Kh2 Ng6 39. Rf2 Nxh4 40. Rxh5 Ng6 41. Rh7+ Ke6 42. Rxb7 Ne5 (42... Rc6!?) 43. Rb6+ Rc6 44. Rxc6+ Nxc6 45. Kg3 Kf7 46. Rc2 Nb4 47. Rd2 Nc6 48. Kf4 Kg6 49. Rd6 Ne5 50. Rxa6 Nf7 51. Ke4 Nh6 52. Ra5 Nf7 53. Ra3 Nd6+ 54. Kf4 Nf5 55. Rd3 Nh6?? { We'll see soon that White's main ideas for breaking the fortress
involve his king busting in via h5 or more rarely e6, and so removing Black's
knight from a circuit that covers these squares turns out to be a fatal error.
It's better to try and hold with the knight on g7 instead. } (55... Ng7!) 56. Rg3+! { White budges the king from the protection of the h5-square, and
as inconsequential as it appears now - it's enough. } 56... Kf7 57. Ke4 Ng8 58. Kf5 (58. Ra3 Kg6 59. Rb3 Kf7 (59... Ne7 60. Rb5! { White refuses to allow ...
Nf5-g7! } 60... Ng8 61. Kd5 Kf7 62. Rb7+ Kg6 63. Ke6 Nh6 64. Rb8 Ng4 65. Rg8+ Kh5 66. Rg7 Kh4 67. Kf5 Ne3+ 68. Kxf6 $18) 60. Kf4 Nh6 { [%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gg5,Gg4] } 61. Rg3 { [%cal Rf7g6] } 61... Ng8 62. Kg4 Ne7 (62... Kg6 63. Kh4+ $18 { [%cal Gg6h6,Gg3g8] }) 63. Kh5 $18) 58... Ne7+ 59. Kf4 (59. Ke4 Ng8 60. Ra3 Kg6 61. Rb3 Ne7 62. Rb5! { [%cal Re7f5,Rf5g7] } 62... Kf7 63. Rb7 Ke6 64. Kf4 Nd5+ 65. Kg4 $18 { and White breaks
in. } { [%cal Gg4h5] }) 59... Nd5+ 60. Kg4?? Kg6 61. Kf3+ Kf7 62. Ke4 Ne7?? (62... Nc7! { [%cal Gc7e6,Ge6g7] } 63. Rc3 Ne6 64. Ra3 Kg6 65. Ra7 Ng7) 63. Kf4 Nd5+ 64. Kf5 Ne7+ 65. Ke4 Ng8 66. Rh3 Kg6 67. Ra3 Kf7 68. Kf4 Nh6 (68... Kg6 69. Rg3+ Kf7 70. Kg4 { is much of
the same. }) 69. Rg3 Ng8 70. Kg4 Ne7 (70... Kg6 71. Kh4+ Kf7 72. Kh5 Ne7 73. Rb3 Ng6 74. Rb7+ Ne7 75. g4 Ke6 76. Rb3 Nd5 77. Kg6 Nf4+ 78. Kg7 Ke5 79. Rb5+ Ke6 80. Rf5 Nd5 81. Rxd5 Kxd5 82. Kxf6 $18) 71. Kh5 Nd5 72. Rf3 Ke6 73. g4 Ke5 (73... Kf7 74. g5 $18) 74. Kg6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


[Event "23rd European Team Chess Championship 20"]
[Site "Terme Catez, Slovenia"]
[Date "2021.11.17"]
[Round "5.5"]
[White "Shirov, Alexei"]
[Black "Erdos, Viktor"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2673"]
[BlackElo "2615"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C92"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Closed, Zaitsev System"]
[StudyName "Awesome Annotations"]
[ChapterName "A.Shirov-V.Erdos"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Evkvf46A/uWnZxhiK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/TonyRo"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Shirov is a known expert on the Ruy Lopez, and plays in a typically classical fashion out of the opening. } 3... a6 (3... Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 { is the now ubiquitous Berlin variation, known best for the ending resulting after } 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 { etc. }) 4. Ba4 (4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O (5. Nxe5? Qd4 { is possibly even better for Black already }) 5... f6 { is the start of the Exchange Variation - not bad but also not popular these days. }) 4... Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 { With 6.Re1, White was legitimately threatening to chop on c6 and then e5. } 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O { [%cal Gd2d4,Gc8g4] } 9. h3 (9. d4 { right away is also possible, but most agree that stopping } 9... Bg4 { first is prudent. }) 9... Re8!? { Signaling the Zaitsev variation, albeit through an uncommon move order. } (9... Bb7 10. d4 Re8 { is a more common move order, though
there's nothing wrong with the text. }) 10. d4 Bb7 11. Ng5!? { [%cal Gb3f7] } 11... Rf8 { [%cal Gh7h6] } 12. Nf3 { White uses this well known repetition to step one move closer to the 40 move
time control. } 12... Re8 13. a3!? { The 4th most popular move, but (and no surprise
here) the 1st pick of Stockfish. White plays a more subtle and slow strategy,
ensuring that White can keep the bishop on the a2-f7 diagonal if necessary,
but also that a transfer to c2 will not allow the very thematic ...exd4 and ...
Nb4. In some cases White can use a3 + Ba2 to prepare to gain more space on the
queenside with b4. } { [%cal Gb3a2] } (13. Nbd2 Bf8 14. a4 h6 15. Bc2 exd4 16. cxd4 Nb4 17. Bb1 c5 18. d5 Nd7 { [%cal Gf7f5] } 19. Ra3 { and now either 19...c4 or 19...f5!? has been the main
line of the Zaitsev for quite some time. } { [%cal Gc5c4,Gf7f5] }) 13... h6 14. Ba2 { The bishop is safe here from ...Na5 or the like in any future lines, and now White gains the option to possibly gain more space on the queenside with b4 if desired. } { [%csl Ga2][%cal Yc6a5] } 14... Bf8 { [%cal Rf6e4,Rb7e4,Re8e4] } 15. d5! { Not only is Black obviously gearing up for counterplay against the e4-pawn after ...exd4, but the Re8/Bf8 constellation do not really gel with White closing the center with d5. } 15... Nb8 16. c4 { [%csl Rb7,Re8] } 16... c6 { Black is pretty much obligated to start chipping away, otherwise the Bb7 also makes a very poor impression. } 17. Nc3 bxc4 18. dxc6 Bxc6 19. Bxc4 $14 { White looks slightly better to, and as such, I'd declare Shirov's 13.a3!? a moderate success. Black is structurally worse. } { [%csl Ga6,Gd6] } 19... Qc7? { Natural, but Shirov
immediately punishes Black for taking his eye off of h4. } (19... Nbd7 20. b4 { was quite a bit better but probably still a little better for White. } { [%cal Gd1b3,Yc1e3,Bf3h2,Bh2g4] }) 20. Nh4! { The night joins the attack, with fatal consequences. } { [%cal Gd8h4] } 20... Bd7 (20... Nbd7 21. Nf5 $40 { was probably a slightly better try for Black but White is still obviously for choice. } { [%cal Gd1f3,Gf3g3,Gg3h4] }) 21. Nd5!! { GENIUS! } 21... Qxc4 (21... Qd8 22. Be3! Nxe4 23. Ng6! Nc5 (23... fxg6 24. Bb6 Qh4 25. Rxe4 Qxe4 26. Nf6+ $18) 24. Nxf8 Rxf8 25. b4 Ne6 26. Bb6 Qg5 27. Re3 $18) 22. Nxf6+ gxf6 23. Qh5 { [%cal Gc1h6,Be1e3,Be3g3] } 23... f5! { A decent defensive try in a very tough position - Black at least stops the rook lift to g3 after his pawn hits the f4-square. } (23... Kh7 24. b3!! Qxb3 25. Bxh6! Bxh6 26. Reb1 Qc4 27. Rb4 Qe6 (27... Qc8 28. Qxf7+ Bg7 29. Nf5 Bxf5 30. exf5 e4 31. Rb7 $18) 28. Nf5 $18) 24. Bxh6?! (24. exf5! Be7 25. Ng6!! { (Perhaps Shirov missed this idea or Rf3! at the end) } 25... fxg6 26. Qxg6+ Kh8 27. Qxh6+ Kg8 28. Re3 Bh4 29. Rf3! $18) 24... Bxh6 25. Qxh6 f4! 26. Nf5? (26. Qg5+ Kf8 27. Qf6 Kg8 28. Nf5 Bxf5 29. exf5 $18) 26... Bxf5 27. exf5 { [%cal Gf5f6] } 27... f6 { [%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rc4] } 28. Qg6+ Kf8 29. Qxf6+ Qf7 30. Qxd6+ Qe7 31. Rad1 Qxd6 32. Rxd6 Ra7 33. g4 Rh7? (33... fxg3! { Black does better to lop off some pawns on the kingside, as otherwise the f4-pawn will likely drop off later. } 34. fxg3 Rh7 35. Kg2 e4 36. Rf6+ Kg7 37. Re6 Rxe6 38. fxe6 Nc6 39. Rxe4 Kf6 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gf6e6] }) 34. Kg2 Nd7 (34... e4!? 35. Rf6+ Kg7 36. Re6 Rxe6 37. fxe6 Nc6 38. Rxe4 $18) 35. b4! { Super precise. } (35. Rxa6 Nc5 { and there are some tricks now that Black's knight is slightly more active, e.g. } 36. Rf6+ (36. Rc6 Nd3 37. Re4 (37. Rd1 e4 $15) 37... Rxh3! { [%cal Gg2h3,Gd3f2] } 38. b4 (38. Kxh3 Nxf2+ 39. Kg2 Nxe4 $19) 38... Kg7 $13) (36. Rd6 e4 $13) 36... Kg7 37. Rd6 Reh8 38. Rh1 f3+ 39. Kxf3 (39. Kg3?? Ne4+ $19) 39... Rxh3+ 40. Rxh3 Rxh3+ 41. Ke2 Rb3 $13) 35... Rc8 36. Red1 { The rest is relatively straightforward - Shirov simply pushes his kingside mass as far as they're allowed. } 36... Rc7 37. g5 e4 38. g6 Rg7 39. h4 Ne5 40. h5 Nd3 41. h6 { [%csl Gf5,Gg6,Gh6] } 41... Rgd7 42. Rxd7 Rxd7 43. h7 (43. f6 $18) 43... Kg7 44. f6+ Kh8 45. Rh1 f3+ { [%cal Gg2h3,Gd3f2] } 46. Kg3 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


