1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nxe5? { The so-called Halloween Gambit. } 4... Nxe5 5. d4 Nc6 6. d5 Ne5 (6... Bb4!? { Recommended by Pinski and Kaufman apparently. Black can also give back the piece here and enjoy reasonable chances for a small advantage. White also has to be very careful here, as you can see in the analysis that follows. It's interesting to note that already in the lichess DB Black scores around 55% from here and even better after move 7. } 7. dxc6 Nxe4 8. Qd4 (8. Qe2? O-O! $19 { [%cal Gf8e8,Ge4c3] }) (8. Qg4 O-O 9. Be2 d5 10. Qf3 bxc6 11. O-O f5 $19) (8. cxd7+ Bxd7 9. Bd2 Bg4!! 10. Be2 (10. f3? Qh4+ $19) 10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Qxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Nxd2 13. Kxd2 O-O-O+ $19) 8... Qe7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bd6 12. cxb7 Bxb7 13. O-O Be5 $15) 7. f4 { This is one of White's main points - the large central pawn mass creates something of a super-charged Alekhine's Defense, except for the fact that White is playing down two points of material. } 7... Ng6 8. e5 Bc5! { [%csl Ye1][%cal Gc5g1] } (8... Ng8 9. d6 { and Black should at least be a little careful here, as a few bad things can happen to you, e.g. } 9... cxd6 10. exd6 { [%cal Gc3b5,Gb5c7,Gd1e2] } 10... Nf6? (10... Qf6!) 11. Qe2+ Be7 12. dxe7 Nxe7 (12... Qxe7 13. f5 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Ne7 15. g4 $18) 13. Be3 O-O 14. O-O-O $16 { [%csl Rd7] }) 9. exf6 O-O { [%csl Gg8,Re1][%cal Gc5f2,Gf8e8] } 10. Be2 $146 { [%cal Gd8f6,Gf8e8] } (10. fxg7 { is way too greedy, for instance } 10... Re8+ 11. Be2 Qh4+ 12. g3 Qh3 $19 { and White's king position is positively terrible. } { [%csl Re1][%cal Gh3g2] }) (10. Qd3 Re8+ 11. Be2 d6 12. Bd2 Qxf6 13. Qg3 b5! { and White's position was on the brink in A.Kopylov -N.Biriukov, Tiumen 2013 }) 10... Qxf6 (10... Re8!? { is also very reasonable. }) 11. Ne4 Qb6 12. Nxc5 Qxc5 { [%csl Ye1][%cal Bc5g1] } 13. Qd3 { [%cal Rc1e3] } 13... Re8 14. Bd2 d6 15. O-O-O Bf5! 16. Qxf5 Rxe2 { [%csl Ge2] } 17. g3 Qc4! $36 { Compare the activity of the pieces and king safety. Black is slightly for preference here in my opinion. } *


