1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Bf5 4. c4 c6 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d3 e6 10. O-O Bc5 11. Nb5 O-O 12. Bf4 h6 { [%cal Gf3e5,Ya2a3,Yb2b4] } 13. Rfc1 Rfc8 14. a3! Ne8 15. b4! $14 { White clearly has the better of it - White's pawns everywhere leave Black's minor pieces slightly worse, and the weakness on b6 is slightly annoying. } 15... Be7 16. Be3 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gf3d4] } 16... Bd8 17. Nfd4 Bg6 18. f4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gg3g4] } 18... Bf6 19. Rab1 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 21. Nxd4 { [%csl Gd4,Rg6,Re8][%cal Rg6d3] } 21... Nd6 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Kf2 Rc3 24. Ra1 Kf8 25. Ke1 Ke7 26. Kd2 Rc8 27. a4 $14 { White is clearly better, with more space everywhere and the better minor pieces. } 27... Ra8 28. a5?! { This allows Black to liquidate the queenside, though even then his problems persist. } (28. g4! { I like this move, grabbing more space and stopping potential ...Nf5 ideas. Black is without active play, so I like to continue ratcheting up the pressure by continued, slow improvement. }) 28... bxa5 29. bxa5 Ra6 30. Kc3 b6! 31. Kb4 bxa5+ 32. Rxa5 Rxa5 33. Kxa5 f6 34. Bh3 Bf7 35. Kb6 g5 36. Bg2 gxf4 37. gxf4 Ne8 38. Bf3 Ng7 39. Kc5 Kd7 40. Bg4 Ke7 41. f5! $16 { After this d5 is simply too weak, and falls. } 41... e5 42. Nc6+ Ke8 43. e3 Kf8 44. Nb4 Ke7 45. Nxd5+ Bxd5 46. Kxd5 Ne8 47. Kc6 Nd6 48. e4 Nf7 49. h4 Nd6 50. Bd1 Nf7 51. Bb3 Nd6 1-0


